  "prompt": "How do I do vibrato on violin?",
  "response": "Learning vibrato on violin takes practice. Here are some steps to help you develop the technique:\n\n1. Basic Positioning\n- Keep your left hand relaxed\n- Make sure your hand is positioned correctly on the fingerboard\n- Maintain a curved, flexible wrist\n\n2. Arm Vibrato (Beginner Method)\n- Place your finger on the string\n- Gently rock your entire arm back and forth\n- Create a small side-to-side motion\n- Start slowly and with minimal movement\n\n3. Wrist Vibrato (Advanced Method)\n- Keep your arm steady\n- Use your wrist to create the oscillating motion\n- Rock your hand back and forth from the base of your finger\n- Start with small, controlled movements\n\n4. Practice Tips\n- Begin practicing on open strings\n- Use a metronome to control speed\n- Start slow and gradually increase speed\n- Practice consistently\n- Use a mirror to check your technique\n\n5. Important Considerations\n- Keep the motion relaxed\n- Don't press too hard on the string\n- Focus on a smooth, even motion\n- Listen for a consistent sound\n\nRemember, learning vibrato takes time and patience. Consider taking lessons from a violin teacher for personalized guidance.",
